    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Say It Isn't So. What's Happening Here?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Doria Asen letter, after reading September 24 Westchester section articles on high-priced college consultants, bicycle tutors and shortage of parking spaces for students at local high schools, holds she must be living in suburban hell (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading the Sept. 24 Westchester section, I poured myself a stiff drink. Five-figure fees paid to a consultant to help a straight-A student with near-perfect SAT scores get into college; tutors to teach the kids of aging baby boomers how to ride a bike; the pressure on 17-year-olds to find a parking spot at their high schools, because only ''loser cruisers'' still take the bus.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After reading the Sept. 24 Westchester section, I poured myself a stiff drink. Five-figure fees paid to a consultant to help a straight-A student with near-perfect SAT scores get into college; tutors to teach the kids of aging baby boomers how to ride a bike; the pressure on 17-year-olds to find a parking spot at their high schools, because only ''loser cruisers'' still take the bus.</p>
        <p>Please, please tell me that I don't live in suburban hell, and, as it was a slow news week, you decided to run an April Fools issue in September.</p>
        <p>DORIA ASEN  Larchmont</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
